{
  "result": "At dawn, the city seems to hold its breath. Delivery trucks idle at corners, bakers lift warm trays from ovens, and the first commuters step into the pale light carrying coffee like a promise. I like that hour because nothing has fully decided what it will become. A street can be noisy or gentle; a day can become ordinary or strange.\n\nRecently I have been thinking about attention as a kind of small hospitality. When we notice the steam rising from a cup, the chipped paint on a railing, or the way a friend pauses before answering, we make room for the world to enter us more completely. This does not solve our problems, but it changes their scale. Worries that looked enormous in the dark sometimes shrink beside a tree full of sparrows.\n\nI am fond of imperfect things: handwritten notes with crossed-out words, uneven sidewalks, gardens that have escaped their borders. Perfection often asks us to admire from a distance, while imperfection invites us closer. It gives the mind a handle, a place to begin.\n\nIf I could prescribe one gentle practice, it would be this: choose one ordinary object each day and study it without trying to improve it. A spoon, a leaf, a bus ticket. Let it be itself. In time, you may discover that your own life, with its dents and weather, also deserves that patient, unhurried regard. Attention, practiced this way, becomes a quiet lamp we carry through rooms we thought we already knew.",
